---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Wage Theft FAQ</h1>

  <h2>What laws protect against wage theft?</h2>
  <p>The federal Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA) sets minimum wage and overtime requirements. Most states have additional wage and hour laws that may be more protective, including higher minimum wages, longer lookback periods, and greater penalties.</p>

  <h2>What is the FLSA lookback period?</h2>
  <p>The FLSA allows recovery of unpaid wages for 2 years before filing, extended to 3 years if the violation was willful. Many states allow 3–6 year lookback periods under state wage laws.</p>

  <h2>What are liquidated damages?</h2>
  <p>Under the FLSA, if your employer cannot show they acted in good faith, you may recover an additional amount equal to your unpaid wages as liquidated damages — effectively doubling your recovery. Many state laws allow even higher penalties (2× or 3× unpaid wages).</p>

  <h2>Can my employer retaliate for filing a wage claim?</h2>
  <p>No. The FLSA's anti-retaliation provisions protect workers who file complaints or participate in investigations. Retaliatory actions (termination, demotion, reduced hours) are themselves violations with additional remedies.</p>

  <h2>Can I file a wage claim on behalf of coworkers?</h2>
  <p>Yes. FLSA collective actions allow similarly situated employees to join together. State law class actions are also available in many states. These cases are more efficient than individual suits and are common for widespread wage theft.</p>

  <h2>How do I file a wage claim?</h2>
  <p>You can file with the U.S. Department of Labor's Wage and Hour Division (WHD) for free, or file a private lawsuit. An employment attorney can advise which route is most beneficial for your situation — attorney fees are recoverable under the FLSA.</p>
</BaseLayout>
